==History==

===Preclassic origins===
{{multiple image
| align = left
| image1 = El Baúl 17.jpg
| width1 = 200
| alt1 = An upright stone slab with faint relief sculpture, badly flaked in places. 
| caption1 = Stela 1 at El Baúl
| image2 = Takalik Abaj Stela 5 p3.jpg
| width2 = 180
| alt2 = An upright stone slab with the front face flat and inscribed with two elaborately dressed figures facing each other, with a double column of hieroglyphs between them.
| caption2 = Stela 5 at Takalik Abaj 
| footer = 
}}
The Maya sculptural tradition that produced the stelae emerged fully formed and had probably been preceded by sculpted wooden monuments.{{sfn|Miller|1999|p=78}} However the tradition of raising stelae had its origin elsewhere in Mesoamerica, among the [[Olmec]]s of the [[Gulf Coast of Mexico]]. In the Late [[Mesoamerican chronology#Preclassic Era or Formative Period|Preclassic]] it then spread into the [[Isthmus of Tehuantepec]] and southwards along the [[Pacific Ocean|Pacific Coast]] to sites such as [[Chiapa de Corzo (Mesoamerican site)|Chiapa de Corzo]], [[Izapa]] and [[Takalik Abaj]] where [[Mesoamerican Long Count calendar]] dates began to be carved onto the stelae. Although at Izapa the stelae depicted mythological scenes, at Takalik Abaj they began to show rulers in Early Classic Maya posture accompanied by calendrical dates and hieroglyphic texts. It was also at Takalik Abaj and Izapa that these stelae began to be paired with circular altars.{{sfn|Miller|Taube|2003|p=157}} By approximately 400&nbsp;BC, near the end of the Middle Preclassic Period, early Maya rulers were raising stelae that celebrated their achievements and validated their right to rule.{{sfn|Sharer|Traxler|2006|pp=182, 197}} At [[El Portón|El&nbsp;Portón]] in the [[Salamá]] Valley of [[Guatemalan Highlands|highland Guatemala]] a carved [[schist]] stela (Monument&nbsp;1) was erected, the badly eroded [[hieroglyph]]s appear to be a very early form of Maya writing and may even be the earliest known example of Maya script. It was associated with a plain altar in a typical stela-altar pairing that would become common across the Maya area.{{sfn|Sharer|Traxler|2006|p=197}} [[Kaminaljuyu Stela 11|Stela 11]] from Kaminaljuyu, a major Preclassic highland city, dates to the Middle Preclassic and is the earliest stela to depict a standing ruler. The sculpted Preclassic stelae from Kaminaljuyu and other cities in the region, such as [[Chalchuapa]] in [[El Salvador|El&nbsp;Salvador]] and [[Chocolá]] in the Pacific lowlands, tend to depict [[Maya politics|political]] succession, [[Sacrifice in Maya culture|sacrifice]] and [[Maya warfare|warfare]].{{sfn|Sharer|Traxler|2006|p=246}}

These early stelae depicted rulers as warriors or wearing the masks and headdresses of [[List of Maya gods and supernatural beings|Maya deities]], accompanied by texts that recorded dates and achievements during their reigns, as well as recording their relationships with their ancestors.{{sfn|Sharer|Traxler|2006|pp=182–183}} Stelae came to be displayed in large ceremonial plazas designed to display these monuments to maximum effect.{{sfn|Sharer|Traxler|2006|p=183}} The raising of stelae spread from the Pacific Coast and adjacent highlands throughout the Maya area.{{sfn|Sharer|Traxler|2006|p=178}} The development of Maya stelae coincides with the development of [[Imperial cult|divine kingship]] among the Classic Maya.{{sfn|Sharer|Traxler|2006|p=183}} In the southern Maya area, the Late Preclassic stelae impressed upon the viewer the achievements of the king and his right to rule, thus reinforcing both his political and religious power.{{sfn|Sharer|Traxler|2006|p=274}}

[[File:Larger Southern Maya area v3.svg|thumb|upright=1.75|Location of the Olmec heartland relative to the southern Maya area|alt=Map showing the locations of the Olmec heartland to the northwest and the southern Maya area southeast of it. The landmass is located in Central America and bordered by the Pacific Ocean to the southwest, the Gulf of Mexico to the northwest and the Atlantic Ocean to the east.]]
At the Middle Preclassic city of [[Nakbe]] in the central lowlands, Maya sculptors were producing some of the earliest lowland Maya stelae, depicting richly dressed individuals.{{sfn|Webster|2002|p=189}} Nakbe Stela&nbsp;1 has been dated to around 400&nbsp;BC. It was broken into pieces, but originally represented two elaborately dressed figures facing each other, and perhaps represents the transference of power from one ruler to his successor, however it also has features that recall the myth of the [[Maya Hero Twins]], and would be the earliest known presentation of them.{{sfn|Drew|1999|pp=129–130}} Around 200&nbsp;BC the enormous nearby city of [[El Mirador|El&nbsp;Mirador]] had started to erect stela-like monuments, bearing inscriptions that appear to be glyphs but that are so far unreadable.{{sfn|Webster|2002|p=188}} Stela dating to the Late Preclassic period are also known from the sites of El Tintal,{{sfn|Justeson|Mathews|1983|p=586}} Cival,{{sfn|Estrada-Belli|2011|p=85}} and San Bartolo{{sfn|Martin|2016|pp=510-511}} in Guatemala, and Actuncan{{sfn|LeCount|2004|pp=32-33}} and Cahal Pech{{sfn|Awe|2009|pp=185-186}} in Belize.

On the Pacific Coast [[El Baúl|El&nbsp;Baúl]] Stela&nbsp;1 features a date in its hieroglyphic text that equates to 36 AD.{{sfn|Drew|1999|p=144}} It depicts a ruler bearing a sceptre or a spear with a double column of hieroglyphic text before him.{{sfn|Sharer|Traxler|2006|p=246}} At Takalik Abaj are two stelae (Stela&nbsp;2 and Stela&nbsp;5) depicting the transfer of power from one ruler to another; they both show two elaborately dressed figures facing each other with a column of hieroglyphic text between them.{{sfn|Sharer|Traxler|2006|p=248}} The Long Count date on Stela&nbsp;2 dates it to the 1st century&nbsp;BC at the latest,{{sfn|Sharer|2000|p=467}} while Stela&nbsp;5 has two dates, the latest of which is 126 AD.{{sfn|Sharer|2000|p=468}} The stela was associated with the burial of a [[human sacrifice]] and other offerings.{{sfn|Justeson|Mathews|1983|p=586}} Stela&nbsp;13 at Takalik Abaj also dates to the Late Preclassic; a massive offering of more than 600 [[Maya ceramics|ceramic]] vessels was found at its base, together with 33 [[Obsidian use in Mesoamerica|obsidian]] [[prismatic blade]]s and other [[Artifact (archaeology)|artefacts]]. Both the stela and the offering were associated with a nearby Late Preclassic [[Takalik Abaj#Royal burials|royal tomb]].{{sfnm|Crasborn|2005|1p=697|Schieber de Lavarreda|2003|2p=784}} At [[Cuello]] in Belize, a plain stela was raised around 100 AD in an open plaza.{{sfn|Justeson|Mathews|1983|p=586}}

At the very end of the Preclassic Period, around 100–300 AD, cities in the highlands and along the Pacific Coast ceased to raise sculpted stelae bearing hieroglyphic texts.{{sfn|Sharer|Traxler|2006|pp=279–280}} This cessation in the production of stelae was the most dramatic symptom of a general decline in the region at this time. This decline has been linked to the intrusion of peoples from the western highlands combined with the disastrous eruption of the [[Lake Ilopango|Ilopango Volcano]] that severely affected the entire region.{{sfn|Sharer|Traxler|2006|p=280}}

===Early Classic===
{{multiple image
| align = right
| image1 = Tikal Stela 31.jpg
| width1 = 180
| alt1 = An upright stone shaft with intricate relief sculpture of a Maya king. 
| caption1 = Stela 31 from Tikal
| image2 = Yaxha stela.jpg
| width2 = 200
| alt2 = An upright stone shaft with the frontal image of a warrior with spear and shield and elaborate feathered headdress.
| caption2 = Stela from [[Yaxha]] depicting a Teotihuacan-style warrior 
| footer = 
}}
In the central [[Petén Basin|Petén]] lowlands, the rise of individual rule at cities like Tikal required the development of new forms of public imagery. Preclassic imagery had involved largely anonymous, impersonal sculpture as an [[Maya architecture|architectural]] element. The existing Preclassic Petén styles of architectural sculpture were combined with features of the highland and Pacific Coast tradition to produce the Early Classic Maya stela.{{sfn|Borowicz|2003|p=218}} Features formerly found on architectural sculpture, such as the giant masks adorning Preclassic pyramids, were adapted for use on stelae. For example, the so-called "[[Maya Jester God|Jester God]]" was transferred to the headdress of the ruler portrayed on Tikal Stela&nbsp;29,{{sfn|Borowicz|2003|p=219}} which bears the oldest Long Count date yet found in the Maya lowlands – equating to 292 AD.{{sfn|Olmedo Vera|1999|p=24}} At some Maya cities the first appearance of stelae corresponded with the foundation of [[Dynasty|dynastic rule]].{{sfn|Borowicz|2003|p=217}}

The standard form of the Maya stela incorporating art, calendrical dates and hieroglyphic text onto a royal monument only began to be erected in the Maya lowlands after 250 AD.{{sfn|Webster|2002|p=119}} The late 4th century saw the introduction of non-Maya imagery linked to the giant metropolis of [[Teotihuacan]] in the [[Valley of Mexico]].{{sfn|Borowicz|2003|pp=222–224}} This foreign influence is seen at Tikal, [[Uaxactun]], [[Río Azul]] and [[El Zapote|El&nbsp;Zapote]], all in the [[Petén Department]] of Guatemala. At Tikal this was initiated by the king [[Yax Nuun Ayiin I|Yax&nbsp;Nuun&nbsp;Ayiin&nbsp;I]], from there it spread to his vassal cities.{{sfn|Borowicz|2003|p=224}} In the 5th century, this strongly Teotihuacan-linked imagery was abandoned by Yax&nbsp;Nuun&nbsp;Ayiin&nbsp;I's son [[Siyaj Chan K'awiil II|Siyaj&nbsp;Chan&nbsp;Kʼawiil&nbsp;II]], who reintroduced imagery associated with the Pacific Coast and adjacent highlands.{{sfn|Borowicz|2003|p=226}} Minor references to Teotihuacan continued, for example in the form of Teotihuacan war emblems.{{sfn|Borowicz|2003|p=227}} His Stela&nbsp;31 was originally erected in 445 but was later broken from its butt and was found buried in the city centre, almost directly above his tomb.{{sfnm|1a1=Drew|1y=1999|1p=195|2a=Miller|2y=1999|2p=96|3a1=Sharer|3a2=Traxler|3y=2006|3p=303}} It depicts the crowning of Siyaj&nbsp;Chan&nbsp;Kʼawiil&nbsp;II, with his father hovering above him as a supernatural being and is executed in traditional Maya style.{{sfn|Drew|1999|pp=195–196}} On the sides of the stela are carved two portraits of his father in a non-Maya style, dressed as a Teotihuacan warrior, bearing the central Mexican [[atlatl]] spear-thrower not adopted by the Maya, and carrying a shield adorned with the face of the Mexican god Tlaloc.{{sfnm|1a1=Drew|1y=1999|1p=196|2a1=Martin|2a2=Grube|2y=2000|2p=35}} The reverse of the stela bears a lengthy hieroglyphic inscription detailing the history of Tikal, including the [[Tikal#Tikal and Teotihuacan|Teotihuacan invasion]] that established Yax Nuun Ayiin I and his dynasty.{{sfn|Martin|Grube|2000|p=34}}

In the Early Classic period the Maya kings began to dedicate a new stela, or other monument, to mark the end of each ''kʼatun'' cycle (representing 7,200 days, just under 20 [[sidereal year]]s).{{sfn|Sharer|Traxler|2006|p=754}} At Tikal, the first to do so was king [[Kan Chitam]] who ruled in the late 5th century. Stela&nbsp;9 from the city is the first dated monument raised to mark off a period of time, it was raised in 475.{{sfn|Borowicz|2003|p=230}}

===Late Classic===
[[File:QuiriguáGlyphs1.jpg|thumb|upright|Hieroglyphic text on the side of Stela E at Quiriguá|alt=The side of a stela, divided into square panels containing sculpted heieroglyphs]]
In the Late Classic the sculpted images of rulers on stelae remained much the same as in the Early Classic, appearing in profile in the foreground and filling almost the entire available space, which is delimited by a frame.{{sfn|Fuente et al.|1999|p=189}} Imagery associated with the [[Mesoamerican ballgame]] started to appear in the Maya lowlands in the Late Classic Period.{{sfn|Cohodas|1991|pp=279–280}} Maya kings are depicted as warriors wearing costume from the Mexican highlands, including elements such as the foreign god [[Tlaloc]] and the [[Feathered Serpent (deity)|Teotihacan serpent]]. Such imagery appears in the Late Classic on stelae from [[Naranjo]], [[Piedras Negras (Maya site)|Piedras Negras]] and the [[Petexbatún]] cities of [[Dos Pilas]] and [[Aguateca]]. At Dos Pilas, a pair of stelae represent the king of the city in costume forming a [[Jaguars in Mesoamerican culture|jaguar]] and eagle pairing, characteristic of the Mexican warrior cult.{{sfn|Cohodas|1991|p=280}} Stelae were being erected by the Maya across the entire central and southern Maya lowlands by 790, an area that encompassed {{convert|150000|km2|sqmi}}.{{sfn|Webster|2002|p=185}}

In the north, [[Coba]] on the eastern side of the [[Yucatán Peninsula]] raised at least 23 large stelae. Although badly eroded their style and texts link them to cities from the Petén Basin.{{sfn|Drew|1999|p=362}} At the southern periphery of the Maya region, Copán developed a new high-[[relief]] style of stelae and in 652 the twelfth king [[Chan Imix Kʼawiil|Chan&nbsp;Imix&nbsp;Kʼawiil]] arranged a series of these stelae to define the sacred geometry of the city, and to celebrate his royal rule and his ancestors.{{sfnm|1a1=Fash|1a2=Agurcia Fasquelle|1y=2005|1p=28|2a=Webster|2y=2002|2pp=164–165}} His son and successor [[Uaxaclajuun Ubʼaah Kʼawiil|Uaxaclajuun&nbsp;Ubʼaah&nbsp;Kʼawiil]] further developed this new high-relief style of sculpture and erected a series of intricately decorated stelae in the city's Great Plaza that brought the carving of stelae close to full in-the-round three-dimensional sculpture.{{sfnm|1a1=Andrews|1a2=Fash|1y=2005|1p=424|2a1=Fash|2a2=Agurcia Fasquelle|2y=2005|2p=28}} Both of these kings focused on their own images on their stelae and emphasised their place in the dynastic sequence to justify their rule, possibly linked to a break in the dynastic sequence with the death of the eleventh king of Copán.{{sfn|Andrews|Fash|2005|p=424}}

After [[Quiriguá]] defeated its overlord Copán in 738, it brought massive blocks of red sandstone from quarries {{convert|5|km|mi}} from the city and sculpted a series of enormous stelae that were the biggest [[Monolithic column|monolithic monuments]] ever raised by the Maya.{{sfnm|Drew|1999|1p=241|Webster|2002|2p=300}} Stela&nbsp;E stands over {{convert|10|m|ft}} high and weighs more than 60 tons. These stelae were shaped into a square cross-section and were decorated on all four faces. These stelae usually bear two images of the Quiriguá king, on the front and the back, in a lower relief than that found at Copán.{{sfn|Drew|1999|p=241}} They feature highly complex panels of hieroglyphic text that are among the most skillfully executed of all Maya inscriptions in stone. The stelae have weathered well and display fine precision on the part of the sculptors.{{sfn|Drew|1999|p=242}}

===Terminal Classic===
{{multiple image
| align = left
| image1 = Tikal St11.jpg
| width1 = 180
| alt1 = A thick stone slab with a rounded top, showing eroded imagery on the front framed by a band of hieroglyphs 
| caption1 = Stela 11 from Tikal, the last to be raised at the city
| image2 = Seibal St.11.jpg
| width2 = 147
| alt2 = An upright stone shaft showing a figure looking to the left, holding a staff in one hand and wearing an elaborate feathered headdress. There are panels of hieroglyphs above and to the left of the figure.
| caption2 = Stela 11 from Seibal, displaying foreign influence 
| footer = 
}}
The decline in the erection of stelae is linked to the decline in the institution of divine kingship, which began in the Late Preclassic. Originally the stelae depicted the king with symbols of power, sometimes standing over defeated enemies and occasionally accompanied by his wives or his heir.{{sfn|Sharer|Traxler|2006|p=500}} By the Terminal Classic, kings were sharing stelae with subordinate lords, who also played a prominent role in the events depicted.{{sfn|Sharer|Traxler|2006|pp=500–501}} This reflected a decentralisation of power and the bargaining between high-ranking nobles so that the king could maintain power, but led to a progressive weakening of the king's rule. As the position of the king became weaker and that of his vassals and subordinates became stronger, the latter began to erect their own stelae, a function that was formerly the exclusive preserve of the king himself. Some of these subordinates broke away to form their own petty states, but even this did not last and they also ceased to erect monuments.{{sfn|Sharer|Traxler|2006|p=501}}

In the [[Pasión River]] region of Petén, rulers began to be portrayed as ballplayers on stelae. [[Seibal]] was the first site in the region to depict its rulers thus.{{sfn|Cohodas|1991|p=279}} Seventeen stelae were erected at Seibal between 849 and 889, and show a mix of Maya and foreign styles, including a lord wearing the beaked mask of [[Ehecatl]], the central Mexican wind god, with a Mexican-style [[speech scroll]] emerging from the mouth. Some of these have a stylistic affinity with the painted murals at [[Cacaxtla]], a non-Maya site in the central [[Political divisions of Mexico|Mexican state]] of [[Tlaxcala]]. This hybrid style seems to indicate that the kings of Seibal were Maya lords adapting to changing political conditions by adopting a mix of symbols originating from both lowland Maya and central Mexican sources.{{sfnm|1a1=Coe|1y=1999|1p=154|2a1=Sharer|2a2=Traxler|2y=2006|2p=522}} Some of the more foreign-looking stelae even bear non-Maya calendrical glyphs.{{sfn|Coe|1999|p=154}} Stelae at [[Oxkintok]], to the north in the [[Puuc]] region of the Yucatán Peninsula, divided the face of the stela into up to three levels, each of which contained a different scene, usually of a lone figure that could be either male or female.{{sfn|Fuente et al.|1999|pp=197–199}} The representation of the human figure differed from the formal treatment in the south, and were simplified, coarse representations lacking individuality amongst sociopolitical and religious symbols.{{sfn|Fuente et al.|1999|p=198}}

As the [[Classic Maya collapse]] swept across the Maya region, city after city ceased to erect stelae recording its dynastic achievements.{{sfn|Sharer|Traxler|2006|p=500}} At the important city of [[Calakmul]], two stelae were raised in 800 and three more in 810, but these were the last and the city fell into silence.{{sfn|Martin|Grube|2000|p=115}} At Oxkintok the last stela was raised in 859.{{sfn|Sharer|Traxler|2006|p=534}} Stela&nbsp;11, dated to 869, was the last monument to ever be erected at the once great city of Tikal.{{sfn|Martin|Grube|2000|p=53}} The last known Maya stelae bearing a Long Count calendrical date are [[Toniná]] Monument&nbsp;101, which was erected in 909 to mark the kʼatun ending that year,{{sfn|Sharer|Traxler|2006|pp=471, 476, 500}} and Stela&nbsp;6 from [[Itzimté]], dated to 910.{{sfn|Fuente et al.|1999|p=186}}

===Postclassic===
At Copán ritual offerings were deposited around the city's stelae until at least 1000, which may represent the offerings of a surviving elite that still remembered its ancestors, or may be due to highland Maya still regarding the city as a place of pilgrimage long after it had fallen into ruin.{{sfn|Webster|2002|p=311}} A small number of sculpted stelae once stood at [[Cerro Quiac]] in the Guatemalan Highlands, and are presumed to have been erected by [[Mam people|Mam Maya]] in the 13th or 14th century.{{sfn|Fox|1978|pp=162–166}} At [[Lamanai]] in [[Belize]], Classic period stelae were repositioned upon two small [[Mesoamerican chronology#Postclassic Era|Postclassic]] platforms dating to the 15th or 16th century.{{sfn|Andres|Pyburn|2005|p=410}} At [[La Milpa, Belize (Maya site)|La Milpa]], also in Belize, at around the time of [[Spanish colonization of the Americas|Spanish contact]] in the late 16th century a tiny remnant Maya population started to make offerings of Conquest-period pottery to stelae, perhaps in an effort to invoke the ancestors to help resist the [[Spanish people|Spanish]] onslaught.{{sfn|Drew|1999|p=354}} A plain stela in Twin Pyramid Group R at Tikal was removed by the local inhabitants some time during the Postclassic; its accompanying altar was also moved but abandoned some distance from its original location.{{sfn|Coe|1967, 1988|p=85}} Some plain stelae were raised at [[Topoxté]] in the Petén Lakes region of Guatemala in the Postclassic; these were perhaps covered in [[stucco]] and painted. This may represent a revival of the ''katun''-ending ceremonies that occurred in the Classic Period, and reflected ties with the northern Yucatán.{{sfn|Sharer|Traxler|2006|p=617}}
{{Clear}}

==Discovery==
One of the earliest accounts of Maya stelae comes from [[Diego Garcia de Palacio]], a Spanish colonial official who described six of the stelae at Copán in a letter to king [[Philip II of Spain]] written in 1576.{{sfn|Drew|1999|p=33}} [[Juan Galindo]], governor of Petén, visited Copán in 1834 and noted the sculpted high-relief stelae there.{{sfn|Drew|1999|pp=51–52}} Five years later, American diplomat [[John Lloyd Stephens]] and British artist [[Frederick Catherwood]] arrived in war-torn Central America and set out for Copán, describing fifteen stelae in Stephens' ''[[Incidents of Travel in Central America, Chiapas and Yucatán]]'', published in 1841.{{sfn|Drew|1999|pp=54–61, 420, 438}} Stephens and Catherwood noticed the presence of red pigment on some of the Copán stelae.{{sfn|Drew|1999|p=64}} Stephens unsuccessfully attempted to buy the ruins of Quiriguá, and purchased Copán for US$50 ($&nbsp;{{formatnum:{{inflation|US|50|1839|r=-2}}}} in {{CURRENTYEAR}}) with the idea of shipping the stelae to [[New York City|New York]] for display in a new museum.{{sfn|Drew|1999|pp=62–63}} In the event, he was prevented from shipping the monuments down the [[Copán River]] by the discovery of impassable rapids and all the stelae remained at the site.{{sfn|Drew|1999|p=52}} While Stephens was engaged on business elsewhere, Catherwood carried out a brief investigation of the stelae at Quiriguá but found them very difficult to draw without a [[camera lucida]] due to their great height.{{sfn|Drew|1999|p=65}} [[Ambrosio Tut]], governor of Petén, and colonel [[Modesto Méndez]], the chief magistrate, visited the ruins of Tikal in 1848 accompanied by [[Eusebio Lara]], who drew some of the monuments there.{{sfn|Drew|1999|pp=86–87}} In 1852 Modesto Méndez went on to discover Stela 1 and Stela 5 at Ixkun.{{sfn|Laporte et al.|2005|pp=163, 208}} English explorer [[Alfred Maudslay]] arrived at Quiriguá in 1881 and cleared the vegetation from the stelae, then travelled on to see the stelae at Copán.{{sfn|Drew|1999|p=89}} In the early 20th century, an expedition by the [[Carnegie Institution for Science|Carnegie Institution]] led by American [[Mayanist]] [[Sylvanus Morley]] discovered a stela at Uaxactun. This period marked a change from the efforts of individual explorers to those of institutions that funded archaeological exploration, excavation and restoration.{{sfn|Drew|1999|p=98}}

==Collections==
{{multiple image
| align = right
| image1 = Ixtonton Stela 2.jpg
| width1 = 100
